The project will assist 10 member States to take targeted actions to eliminate the worst forms of child labour. This will be achieved by providing critically needed and technical guidance support in the areas of legislation, enforcement, monitoring, development and implementation of national action plans, and improved implementation of policies and social programs with an impact on child labour. This proposal is organized under four components that are mutually reinforcing. The first component will improve specific aspects of national legislation on child labour including its worst forms so that the national legislative framework is in compliance with international standards. The second component will improve monitoring and enforcement of laws and policies related to child labour through improving the capacity of national inspection systems as well as establishing/improving child labour monitoring systems. The third component will build national capacity to develop, validate, adopt and implement their National Action Plans on the elimination of child labour. The forth component aims to enhance implementation of national and local policies and programs and to improve social policies and programs that will have a positive impact on child labour (such as basic education policies and programs, vocational training, social protection services, and employment creation and poverty reduction initiatives). The Project will be implemented by the ILO through its International Program on the Elimination of Child Labour (IPEC), assisted by other relevant ILO units, offices and specialists.

Department of Inspection for Factories and Enterprises (DIFE) developed 5 Standard Operating Procedure (SOP) on labour inspection, factory licensing, layout plan approval, accident investigation and complaints investigation and published on its website. 

DIFE published 2018-19 LI annual report (Bengali version) and 2019-2020 will be published by December 2021. 

As of June 2021, total 8,241 inspections were carried out using the Labour Inspection Management Module (LIMA). In order to improve the current version of LIMA, DIFE has been working to review LIMA and update it to version 2.0 by Dec 2021. 

A clustered training platform named Learning Hub (LH) was established and launched by BGMEA and BKMEA to respond to COVID-19 crisis in the RMG sector in Bangladesh. As of June 2021, the trained master trainers reached out to a total of 5408 worker-management representatives (46% female) in over 420 RMG factories with virtual training on (i) COVID-19 Awareness, (ii) Return to Work OSH and (iii) Managing Labour Relations.

DIFE provided Foundational Training (FT) to 30 new Labour Inspectors including 4 female from Feb to April 2021 on service rules of the Bangladesh government and the functions and business processes of the national labour inspectorate, etc. 

Department of Labour (DOL) established an online publicly accessible database of registered trade unions. The database is in testing stage and will be fully functional by this year.
 The ILO with the support of the Government of Canada, United Kingdom, and the Netherlands provided technical support to DIFE to develop these SOPs

The ILO provided quality assurance support to DIFE publishing the annual reports. 

The ILO with the support of the Government of Canada, United Kingdom, and the Netherlands, provided technical support to establishing and upgrading this online application for the management of the Labour Inspection system in Bangladesh through the Labour Inspection Management Module (LIMA).

The ILO led the initiative for establishing the Learning Hub to provide and coordinate capacity building supports to the constituents. The ILO provided training and follow up support to develop 164 tripartite Master Trainers (29% female) for delivering 03 courses under COVID-19 Training Package. 

The ILO provided technical supports including facilitations of several sessions on LIMA, gender, compliance issues among other topics. Since 2015, this FT has built the capacity of 268 labour inspectors (42 women, 226 men) to date. 

The ILO provided technical support to DOL in establishing the online database. The technical support included to review of the database structure against the BLA
Inputs on the database structure in alignment with the trade union registration SOP

In  November 2022, the Ghana Trades Union Congress (TUC) developed a tool for undertaking a comprehensive analysis of existing collective bargaining agreement (CBA) clauses from nine sectors (two CBAs from the Maritime and Dockworkers Union (MDU), two from the Timber and Woodworkers’ Union (TWU), two from General Agricultural Workers’ Union (GAWU), two from Union of Industry, Commerce and Finance (UNICOF), and one from the Public Services Workers’ Union) to assess the extent to which CBA clauses are still relevant tools for providing tailored needs driven services to existing, new and potential membership. 

Obsolete clauses were updated and revitalised with new clauses addressing new issues in the world of work, including ending violence and harassment, and enhancing safety and health.  From July 2023, the updated CBAs were utilised as tools for organising and attracting new groups of workers resulting in increased unionisation of over 1000 young workers in non standard forms of employment  such as domestic work, gig work, informal economy, temporary and contract based work where the majority of non-unionised groups are located. Ghana TUC has increased membership by 12% and enhanced services packages for improved working conditions and services for young women to report and receive counselling and support on issues related to violence and harassment. The ILO Country policy responses presented within the four pillars of action defined by the ILO to lessen the impact of COVID-19 on businesses, jobs and the most vulnerable members of society provided a useful framework and guidance during the CBA analysis in defining new clauses for integration into existing Collective Bargaining Agreements. During the months of February to May 2023, ILO supported several workshops for fifty trade union industrial relations officers, social partner negotiators and researchers to deepen knowledge and understanding on social dialogue and collective bargaining based on the lessons learnt from the COVID-19 pandemic.

1. 1.	In January 2023 the government, led by Ministry of Community Development, Gender, Women and Special Groups adopted and operationalised a National Multisectoral Generation Equality Program (TGEP) 2022-2026 which considered the priorities for ratification of Convention 190 through sensitization and awareness raising.  As a result, a National Advisory Committee consisting of 25 members (19 members from Tanzania mainland and six members from Zanzibar), as well as experts from different sectors was created to oversee the measures geared for achieving gender equality including through promotion for ratification of C.190 and integration of the key principles into national action plans. Sensitization and awareness raising for constituents have therefore been promoted for the ratification of C190 and R206.

2. To ensure the effective implementation of Convention No. 190 and create a world of work free from violence and harassment for all and, in particular, women,  in December 2023 the government in consultation with Association of Tanzania Employers (ATE) and Trade Union Congress of Tanzania (TUCTA) adopted a National Action Plan on ending Violence against Women and Children in Tanzania (NPA-VAWC 2023/2024 – 2027/2028). The NPA-VWAC II shapes strategic interventions clustered into different thematic areas including creating safe environment in public and digital spaces and integrated issues of HIV and AIDS as cross-cutting areas as efforts to creating decent work environment for vulnerable workers in the informal sector. The NPA-VAWC II takes into consideration the key principles of the ILO Convention No. 190 and Recommendation No. 206.
 With support from ILO RBTC funds, the ILO in collaboration with UNWOMEN, Ministry of Community Development, Gender, Women and Special Groups, Association of Tanzania Employers (ATE), Trade Union Congress of Tanzania (TUCTA) and other stakeholders convened a national workshop for awareness raising of ILO C190 which also informed and integrated in the URT Generation Equality Programme (2021/22 – 2025/26) approved and adopted in January 2023.
 
The ILO provided technical support during drafting of the NPA-VWAC II and facilitated participation of the social partners to make strategic inputs in the document which integrated issues of elimination of sexual harassment and violence at public spaces as one of the strategic thematic area of focus on the NPA-VAWC II. The ILO C.190 and its recommendation were used as references to inform the process.

- 14 Master trainers from Council of Indian Employers and 11 central trade unions in India built capacity for organising in India's informal economy and advancing social dialogue.
- Tripartite constituents in India availed access to distance learning material on collective bargaining, workplace cooperation and grievance handling translated into Hindi as a basis for self-paced learning.
- Officials of Mumbai Port Authority and trade unions of Port of Mumbai jointly developed an action plan for grievance handling procedures for the Port of Mumbai
 - The ILO organized a bipartite the training of master trainers on a toolkit to promote social dialogue in India’s informal economy. This was undertaken in partnership with an implementing partner – Sampark Livelihoods Promotion Trust on 14-16 September 2023. The trainers developed their respective action plans to take forward training in their respective organisations.

- The ILO supported the translation and access to the distance learning material on collective bargaining and grievance handling through a collaboration with ITC-ILO.

- The ILO facilitated a self-assessment of the existing grievance handling procedures and supported the development of grievance handling procedures for the Port of Mumbai on 1-3 February 2023.

(1) A COVID-19 social cash transfer (CT) was successful delivered by the Ministry of Social Solidarity and Inclusion (MSSI), between June and July 2020, to a total of 98 percent of all eligible households in Timor-Leste (approximately 313,456 families). 

(2) The National Social Protection Strategy (NSPS) 2021-2030 was approved by the Council of Ministers on 11 November 2021. It is guided by R.202. It has been developed in consultation with the social partners since 2016.

(3) The Ministry of Social Solidarity and Inclusion (MSSI) launched in July 2021 a new generation of the Pilot Cash Transfer Bolsa da Mae Program for universal coverage targeting pregnant women, children up to 6 years and children with disabilities . A gradual expansion will start with under 3 years old in 2022 and will reach under 6 years old in 2025. In 2022, it is estimated to cover 6,934 pregnant women, 20,476 children under 3 and 5,154 children with disability. In 2024, it is estimated to cover 7,157 pregnant women, 34,678 children under 5, 5,319 children with disability. Monthly amounts will be paid as US$15 during pregnancy, US$20 per child and US$10 for disability. (1) With the support from the COVID-19 Multi Partner Joint Trust Fund, ILO led the development partners from the UN side and provided direct technical assistance throughout the design, implementation and evaluation of the COVID-19 social cash transfer (CT). 

(2) With funding from the Government of Portugal, ILO provided direct technical assistance and capacity building to the revision and completion of the NSPS.

(3) ILO contributed with technical inputs to the design proposal developed by DFAT-MSSI on the new generation of Bolsa da Mae program,  resulting in the simplification of the initial proposed designed. 

ILO supported the MSSI to explore options to extend coverage and improve the benefit amount of the current national CT Bolsa da Mae program, as well as to estimate the financial impact of the different options.
4) ILO supported the MSSI to organize an international seminar "General Basis of Social Protection: Future Perspectives and International Experiences" on 5th of August 2021. This seminar aimed to contribute to a better understanding about the general bases, principles, objectives, and structure of the social protection system in Timor-Leste. Key national and international decision-makers, leaders and officials participated at the international seminar.

14 Government TVET institutes are offering Entrepreneurship Development Training (EDT) using SYIB to the youths. 1200 youths (25% female) have already received the EDT from these institutes. With the support of European Union Delegation (EUD), ILO developed partnership with the relevant government agencies and TVET institutes in implementing the intervention on EDT. For this ILO developed the capacity of 13 govt. TVET Masters trainers on SYIB manual who trained 60 Trainers to roll out EDT in the TVET institutes.

1) Amidst the COVID pandemic, the Fiji Trade Union Congress (FTUC) carried out an analysis through a Rapid Assessment (RA) on the impact of COVID-19 on employment and their membership. Based on the findings of 3,000 FTUC member's from the most affected sectors recommendations were proposed through representation and submissions of proposals to the Government of Fiji (Ministry of Economy) to include the said proposals in the for the 2020/21 national budget/COVID-19 stimulus package designs, where nearly one third of the proposed solutions have been accepted by the government. 

2) Initially, FTUC was able to coordinate and assess training needs of 1,420 redundant workers in Fiji, of which 54% of the workers sought direct assistance of some form from the FTUC. In extending new services and building upon the need to reach out to new memberships, the FTUC signed a bipartite MOU with the Fiji Employers Federation to support redundant workers who have started micro enterprises in the informal sector, through a bipartite initiative called "Transition to Business (T2B)".

3) The above initiative, led to proof of concept to influence policy makers, especially in the UN, to support a larger project (U$2.5m) targeting inform sector workers and extending services. The renewed interest, led to a Multi Partner Trust Fund (MPTF) Project to be launched in Fiji in which FTUC is a lead partner. As a result of the activities carried out by the MPTF Project, FTUC continues to reach out to the informal sector workers and through the new services of business development and rights coordination and greater digital usage.  

4) The FTUC (4 members, including youths) was supported to engage in national level discussions on SDG and contribute to the national and CSO report on the Voluntary National ILO Suva through initially from the RBSA Project and later through the MPTF Project and ACTRAV support and technical advice continues to support the FTUC in reaching out and expanding their service delivery to the informal sector workers.  The technical advice and interventions include the design of the initial concept on the employments services, the methodology and outreach strategies to the informal sector, planning and integrating SDG and Youth concerns in working out of informality, addressing and strengthen freedom of association and ensuring greater expansion of trade unionism, and potential digital tools development for outreach to informal economy workers.

1. An analysis of the effectiveness of existing Tripartite consultative committees at the federal and provincial levels is produced and used by the Governments to discuss and revisit the use of these fora to meet the objectives set out in the TORs for these structures and to uphold the requirements of C144. 
2. Government established and notified an FOA/CB's government committee. The committee is overseeing the process of engagement with provincial stakeholders and social partners gradually but steadily carrying out discourses on changes in the existing law that will result in significant reforms on freedom of association and collective bargaining.
3. Social dialogue has been strengthened in 47   factories through formation of worker-management committees which is being used to bring meaningful changes at the unit level and to address enterprise-based issues.
4.  Improving capacities of EOs and WOs to support compliance and influence compliance through dialogue at sectoral levels to support both EO and WO to better represent their members. This includes support to the implementation of the Memorandum of Understanding agreed by the Government of Pakistan and provincial governments of Sindh and Punjab. 
5.  Workers and Employers Bilateral Council of Pakistan(WEBCOP) and MNE Declaration focal point strengthened through the development of an action plan including the area of grievance handling/dispute resolution and industrial relations. • With support of the EU, the ILO facilitated capacity development of members of all Provincial Tripartite Consultative Committees (PTCC) and Federal Tripartite Consultative Committee (FTCC) on international labour standards (ILS), reporting obligations, ILO supervisory bodies, the 2023 ILS reporting obligation. 
• The briefing note on FTCC and PTCC has informed the Government about the working of these dialogue forums, capturing the current situation, and practices as well as identifying areas for future improvement of the mechanism.
The briefing note aims to provide a summary of the current situation and practices within the Federal Tripartite Consultative Committee (FTCC) and Provincial Tripartite Consultative Committees (PTCCs) in Pakistan. It also identifies areas for future improvement. The objective is to enhance the utilization of FTCC and PTCC for strengthening the implementation and reporting on the ILS, discussing ILS ratifications, and improving coordination between the federal centre and provinces on these issues.
 The Government is using the briefing note to engage tripartite committee members at federal and provincial level to discuss challenges that can be collectively addressed to make these committees more effective  
• ILO developed a technical note on freedom of associations and collective bargaining (FOA/CB) and facilitated consultations for government, workers, and employers’ representatives.
• ILO facilitated consultation on labour statistics concerning GSP+ compliance data collection. ILO developed a concept note on a pilot test of modules related to collective bargaining, freedom of association, forced labour and child labour in two provinces.

1. A guideline on establishment and functioning of bipartite workplace cooperation committee at the enterprise level has been endorsed by the employers' and workers representatives from the Federation of Nepalese Chamber of Commerce (FNCCI), Nepal Trade Union Congress (NTUC), General Federation of Nepalese Trade Unions (GEFONT) and the All Nepal Trade Union Federation (ANTUF) at a tripartite virtual meeting held on the 7th July 2021. In addition, the employers' and the workers' representatives have agreed to pilot the implementation of workplace cooperation committees in selected enterprises in 2022.
Further, they have agreed to launch an awareness raising campaign on workplace cooperation, with the participation of workplace-level social partners from selected enterprises to share good practice, challenges and opportunities of workplace cooperation mechanisms.

2. A guideline on establishment and functioning of grievance handling mechanism for enterprises prepared, and endorsed on 7th July by the tripartite representatives of the Federation of Nepalese Chamber of Commerce and Industry (FNCCI), Nepal Trade Union Congress (NTUC), General Federation of Nepalese Trade Unions (GEFONT) and the All Nepal Trade Union Federation (ANTUF). The tripartite constituents additionally agreed to pilot these guidelines. The guidelines provide direction to enterprises on the development of enterprise-level grievance handling procedures.

3. Bipartite agreement concluded between Joint Trade Union Coordination Centre (JTUCC), Federation of Nepalese Chambers of Commerce and Industry (FNCCI), and Confederation of Nepalese Industries (CNI) that resolved wage payment and other issues raised during the lockdown in 2020. 1. The ILO provided technical support, ensuring that the guideline is in compliance with ILO Conventions and Recommendations, to draft the guideline and align it with the Labour Act 2017, which provides a legal framework on the formation of labour-relation committee at the enterprise level. The guideline was workshopped with the tripartite constituents and is based on the ILO's Industrial Relations Toolkit. The ILO facilitated the tripartite consultation meeting and presented the guideline to the tripartite representatives. Further, it conducted an awareness sessions on workplace cooperation with the ILO constituents. Turin Centre also developed a self-learning module on workplace cooperation, based on the ILO's Industrial Relations Toolkit and customized to Nepali context.       
  		
2. Grievance handling guidelines, prepared by the ILO, were endorsed by the tripartite constituents in July 2021. The guideline was workshopped with the tripartite constituents and is based on the ILO's Industrial Relations Toolkit. The ILO contribution includes an awareness session on the 7th July 2021 that was conducted on grievance handling, and the technical support that was provided to draft the guidelines. 

The ILO, with the support of the Turin Centre, also developed a distance learning module on grievance handling, based on the ILO's Industrial Relations Toolkit, specifically customised for Nepal. 

3. ILO facilitated a bipartite dialogue between Joint Trade Union Coordination Centre (JTUCC), Federation of Nepalese Chambers of Commerce and Industry (FNCCI), and Confederation of Nepalese Industries (CNI) to resolve labour relations challenges arising from COVID-19.

The ILO’s biennial Programme Implementation Report is an instrument of accountability. It describes the performance of the Organization against the commitments made in the Programme and Budget documents for the corresponding biennial period.

The ILO’s Decent Work Results Dashboard –complementing the ILO’s Programme Implementation Report – presents information on the results achieved and on the most significant outputs delivered by the ILO during the relevant biennium.
The ILO’s Results Framework is always part of the Programme and Budget (P&B) document for the relevant biennium. Please refer to the Annex “Results Framework” of the relevant P&B Document
